                  {
                     "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 4: One more irrefutable proof, until someone refutes it</b><br /><br />The oldest estimated period in the Folsom excavations for the Paleoindians is between <htdate0> and <htdate1>, although there is still presence of more recent clay and organic matter (<htcite0>).<br /><br />Between <htdate2> and <htdate3>, the Moche culture in Peru also used <i>atlatls</i> as shown in the hands of a warrior in <b>Figure 7</b> (<htcite1>).<br /><br />Upon reading these two pieces of information, did you come to the conclusion that the Moche culture learned from or inherited elements from the Folsom culture?<br /><br />If so, did you take into account the more than 4,000 years between them?<br /><br />Did you take into account that, although we show a Moche <i>atlatl</i>, at no point did we present a Folsom atlatl for comparison?<br /><br />Did you consider that different peoples could have reached the same conclusion independently due to the long time interval?</div></div></center></p>",
                     "source": [
